article.description: It was only a matter of time before one of the Phoenix Mercury shooters got hot, Anna DeForge insisted.
article.headline: DeForge scores career-high 26 points
article.linkText: Mercury send Liberty to record sixth straight loss
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- It was only a matter of time before one of the
Phoenix Mercury shooters got hot, Anna DeForge insisted.

It turned out to be her. DeForge made five of six 3-pointers in
the second half, helping her team to a 30-point turnaround and
sending the New York Liberty to their franchise-record sixth
straight loss.

DeForge had nine of her career-high 26 points in a 23-7
second-half run, and the Mercury beat New York 72-60 Thursday
night.

"With the all the shooters we have, it was bound to happen,"
he said.

DeForge had 21 points in the second half for Phoenix, which
overcame a 20-4 deficit.

"We have to find a way to have the mental skills to get
ourselves highly energized to play," Mercury coach Carrie Graf
said. "To dig ourselves out of a hole like that shows character,
but I'd rather have it the other way around."

New York played without Crystal Robinson, the team's
third-leading scorer at 10.3 points a game. She sat out with a
broken right pinkie finger.

No. 1 draft pick Diana Taurasi added 20 points for the Mercury,
who scored the first nine points of the second half and led by as
many as 14. DeForge tied a franchise mark with five 3-pointers and
also had five rebounds and five assists.

Becky Hammon had 20 points and seven rebounds for New York,
which missed 21 of 31 shots in the second half and made 16
turnovers that led to 15 Mercury points. Vickie Johnson had 18
points and seven rebounds for the Liberty, who outrebounded Phoenix
36-29.

"They heated up," said Hammon, who led New York to its quick
start. "We didn't buckle down. We lost our swagger there in the
second half and we can't let that happen. We got a lead and we just
sit on it instead of keep attacking.

"Instead of sticking to what got us there, we started playing
tentative."

Phoenix made 20 of 25 free throws to New York's six of 10.

"They played excellent defense," Liberty coach Richie Adubato
said. "They broke us down and we didn't have the veteran
leadership on the floor to counter some of the defensive moves that
they made."

Johnson's layup with 15:31 remaining gave New York a 38-37 lead,
but Adubato was hit with a technical and Phoenix scored the next
nine points -- seven by DeForge -- to take a 46-38 lead with 13:09
remaining. New York never got closer than five points thereafter.

The Liberty ran out to a 20-4 lead, taking advantage of
Phoenix's slow start. The Mercury missed 11 of their first 13 shots
while Hammon scored five points, grabbed five rebounds and had
three assists in the first 8 minutes.

Hammon had 13 points on 5-of-7 shooting in the first half but
Taurasi scored six points in the final 1:02 to get Phoenix within
34-26 at the break.
